{"action":"opened","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760/events","html_url":"https://github.com/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760","id":2748815685,"node_id":"I_kwDOCpMuHc6j15lF","number":5760,"title":"LFortran returns the location of a symbol's declaration instead of its definition","user":{"login":"dylon","id":516519,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjUxNjUxOQ==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/516519?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon","html_url":"https://github.com/dylon","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dylon/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2024-12-18T21:53:31Z","updated_at":"2024-12-18T21:53:31Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"For variables, LFortran returns the locations of their declarations instead of their definitions. Consider the following snippet:

```fortran
program expr2
  implicit none

  integer :: program

  program = (2+3)*5
  print *, program

end program

```

LFortran returns the following:

```shell
lfortran --show-document-symbols /var/tmp/expr2.f90 | jq
[
  {
    "kind": 12,
    "location": {
      "range": {
        "start": {
          "character": 1,
          "line": 0
        },
        "end": {
          "character": 11,
          "line": 8
        }
      },
      "uri": "uri"
    },
    "name": "expr2"
  },
  {
    "kind": 13,
    "location": {
      "range": {
        "start": {
          "character": 14,
          "line": 3
        },
        "end": {
          "character": 20,
          "line": 3
        }
      },
      "uri": "uri"
    },
    "name": "program"
  }
]
```

If you consider the location of the `program` symbol, it gives the range of characters representing its identifier in its declaration. Instead, it would be preferable if it would return the range of characters representing its definition `program = (2+3)*5`:

```json
  {
    "kind": 13,
    "location": {
      "range": {
        "start": {
          "character": 3,
          "line": 5
        },
        "end": {
          "character": 19,
          "line": 5
        }
      },
      "uri": "uri"
    },
    "name": "program"
  }
```

We could consider returning the locations of both a symbol's declaration and definition. That would be useful information, too.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5760/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null}}

